This restaurant deserves to get its first Michelin star! All the products were not only very tasty, but the products also contained a unique blend of Norhern Thai-style flavors (which are in my opinion the better dishes of Thailand). We felt really treated like kings. The service was impeccable and no waiting thanks to the digital bell on our dining table. As a starter, we ate the soft, creamy and scrumptious eggplant salad, which I can really recommend to vegetarians. Also the chicken skewers with satay sauce was a great addition to our order, with a wink to the original chicken-satay skewers from Indonesia. Even the pickled veggies let me think of the Indonesian dishes for a while. However, I have to confess that I personally prefer an Indonesian-style satay sauce. For our main course we had a great stir-fried chicken dish with a great combination of spices. To add more spice to our dinner, we had the delicious Kang Nor curry dish. I really like this curry for the added bamboo sprouts and dried fish. As a non-pork eater, I obviously chose this fish-variety. However, they also have a pork-variety. My boyfriend and I were seated inside. The restaurant was well climatized and very clean. You could even look through the glass, where you could see the diligent people working hard to make exquisite dishes. Even the dining tables were of another kind of level. At the end of our dinner we realized that we had been sitting on a ‚Äòremade‚Äô authentic sewing table. It gives the restaurant so much more atmosphere. As a dessert, I ate colored soft noodles in sweet coconut milk. I must say that this type of dessert, has it all to me. We went to our hotel totally satisfied, joyful and fully fed. I can assure everyone that you will enjoy your meal here to the highest level!

Table management is quite systematic, you can call the waiter by pressing the button (but it takes time for them to come) Food, I would say it's authentic Northern Thai Style food. With its open kitchen you can see the cleanliness. Price, well it's not a normal food stall or street food. So the price is reasonable.

Exceptional traditional northern style restaurant with a Michelin guide recommendation. It's both traditional looking and smart and the service is friendly. I ordered the softshell crab Khao soi and the ong pu, grilled paddy crab head butter. Both excellent dishes, well presented and tasted phenomenal. The ong pu in particular was creamy, intense and felt luxurious. Will definitely be back.

This bustling Northern Thai eatery delivers a lively, tourist-friendly intro to Kao Soi. The Super Bowl featured an assortment of grilled pork, chicken leg, and squid which offers a creamy, slightly sweet coconut-curry broth with firm egg noodles is approachable for newcomers, though purists might miss traditional depth. Portions are generous, and seating was immediate during our 2pm visit. Don‚Äôt skip the aromatic chicken satay skewers - tender white meat with a zesty chili-shallot dip. Highlights include the crab shell roe (tiny but intensely savory) and the peeled coconut‚Äîa refreshing, Instagrammable orb in a chilled metal cup. The vibe is energetic, with English menus and swift service, though prices lean higher than local joints. The ambience was pretty with all the overhanging ferns and plants however seated outdoors, there were a little too many flies around for comfort. Small eaters can share the Super Bowl (it‚Äôs huge!), skip the crab roe unless craving novelty, and visit mid-afternoon to avoid crowds. Ideal for first-timers seeking a hassle-free Kao Soi experience, but seasoned diners might prefer hole-in-the-wall authenticity. Still, a solid choice for flavorful, filling meals in a vibrant setting.

TL;DR: Tasty meal in a comfortable atmosphere. Kao Soy Nimman has an extensive menu. More options than I expected. We settled on the Kao Soy Gai (chicken) and an order of chicken satay and beef skewers. We enjoyed all of the dishes. Service was friendly and helpful. Overall, it was a good meal. A solid 3.5 - 4 stars!

Housed in trendy Nimman, this is one of Chiang Mai‚Äôs Michelin-picked noodle playground that gives a modern spin to the Northern Thai classic: khao soi‚Äîa dish rooted in Lanna history, once brought over by Chinese-Muslim traders, now a Chiang Mai must-eat. Kicked things off with the Octopus Khao Soi‚Äîbecause why be normal when you can have tentacles in your soup? The octopus was chewy, not salty and a little bougie in the best way laying on top of a coconut curry hot tub. Then came the classic hero: the Chicken Khao Soi. A+ comfort food. That broth? Creamy, warm, just the right punch of spice. At some parts, the slurping was wishing the broth had just one more ladle of richness. Ended with a tropical pool party where the Thub Thim Krob came in like a treasure chest disguised as a dessert bowl.Signature ruby water chestnuts (crunchy, chewy, glorious) Grass jelly, cendol, and nata de coco and golden jackfruit pieces all vibing in one icy, sweet coconut milk party. Was definitely pleasing to the eyes but flavour wise went a little under. Still‚Äîworth the visit, especially if you‚Äôre khao soi-curious or full-on obsessed with the michelin adventure! Zoom off with a grab-bike ride that gives u more than local vibes üòâ

This restaurant has an amazing Northern Thai menu, but is especially well known for its many choices regarding their speciality dish, Kao Soi. You can order it almost any way that you like, with or without meat. They offer Kao Soi with tofu, mushrooms, or just vegetables for all of us vegetarians. There are other vegetarian options on their menu, also. We really enjoyed the vegetable Thai omelette! Very delicious! It‚Äôs a busy place because it is so popular, so arrive early if you don‚Äôt like to wait. Service was very good because every table has a call button for the waiters, and they always respond almost immediately. Prices were very good, too. We will definitely return here and recommend this place to others.

Khaosoy itself is ok, a lot less spicy compared to other khaosoy places. Im Thai, the overall taste is quite bland for me, but I assume tourists might like it. Chicken satay is very bland.üòÖ Good service. (if not rushing hours ofc) Price is normal, portion is normal, not too much or too less.
If you looking for some traditional Thai food, Kao Soy Nimman is an option that‚Äôs worth trying. The food served kinda quick but the staffs are bit busy so you have to be patient.

Kao Soy Nimman is a must-visit for anyone looking to experience the authentic flavors of Northern Thailand. This charming restaurant delivers the perfect blend of tradition and taste, making it a standout spot for Thai food lovers. The Food Their signature dish, Kao Soy, is a masterpiece. The creamy, curry-like broth is rich with spices, perfectly balanced, and full of depth. The crispy noodles on top add a delightful crunch, while the tender meat melts in your mouth. Every spoonful is packed with the bold, authentic flavors that define Northern Thai cuisine. The Drinks Adding to the experience, drinks are served in traditional Thai-style bowls. This small but thoughtful detail enhances the cultural vibe of the meal, making it feel special and unique. Whether you opt for a Thai iced tea or a refreshing herbal drink, the presentation is sure to impress. Why Visit? ‚Ä¢ Authentic Taste: The Kao Soy here truly captures the essence of Northern Thai flavors. ‚Ä¢ Unique Presentation: Serving drinks in Thai traditional bowls adds a fun and cultural touch. ‚Ä¢ Great Atmosphere: The warm and inviting ambiance makes it a great place for a casual meal or introducing friends to Thai cuisine.

We had a short Que, Took 10 min to get our order in but the place was busy. The food was good, I enjoyed my khao soi, the chicken satay was really good. Only negatives were they don‚Äôt accept credit cards and bathroom was dirty. Others I‚Äôd give 5 star. Prices little high but food was good quality.

The portions are VERY small and the price is high for what they offer. I found this khao soi very mediocre. It‚Äôs not bad. It is just nothing special at all. I believe this place is overrated and I had a feeling it would be‚Ä¶ but I decided to give it a try and believe in the reviews. I was wrong. People keep coming because there are some good reviews and, if they had not had a chance of actually having a good thai meal or a rich khao soi, they would think this one is good. Believe me, its not. And if you come to this restaurant and there is a line, dont wast your precious time.
The best Khao Soi we had in Chiang Mai (which says a lot because they were all great). It is slightly more expensive than other places we tried but the taste in return is definitely worth it.

Some of the best northern Thai food I've had! The Khao SOI was delicious but the garlic pepper pork and Thai northern sausages were heavenly! One of the best meals I've had in Thailand

Michelin-rated restaurant. Visited on 28 Feb 2025 at 6pm. High turnover, so don‚Äôt have to wait too long. We saw many tourists and some locals having their meal here. Tables were re-purposed from old sewing machines. Eight of us had a bowl of the famous Kao Soy Kai (curry noddlenwith chicken leg), as well as some side dishes to share: steamed herbal beef shank, chicken satay, kai jeow moo sab (minced pork Thai omelette). The Kao Soy Kai is a mixture of crispy noodle and normal yellow noodle. Blended well curiously. The ingredients were fresh, and the meat dishes were cooked well. We also ordered a drink each, and some dessert to share. Disappointed that the mango sticky rice was sold out. Price wise, it is reasonable: total of about 2,800 baht or 350 baht per person.
This place is nicely done up. Served nice Curry Noodle, the satay is a must to order as well. Simply love the buttery pea drink. So refreshing! Price is very reasonable as well!

Delicious khao soi at reasonable rates! One bowl costs somewhere around 100 baht & it's very filling with a sufficient quantity of protein! You can also opt for a vegetarian one if you'd like! The curry (broth) of the khao soi is flavorful and is definitely the USP of this restaurant. I also tried their chicken satay which tasted tender and slightly sweet. Great, overall! I visited on a weekday evening and did not see any queues/wait time. Service is quick with efficient & polite waiters!

This is a popular place to eat, we arrive 30 minutes early for dinner with friends.. there was a long queue ahead of us, and because one member of our party had a plane to catch, we wanted to avoid being delayed, but as soon as we joined the queue we were shown to a table for 4.. this was because the people ahead of us needed a much larger table together. This was fine, there was no pressure to 'free' the table, we had drinks while we waited.. 1 x beer and 1 x Grass Jelly Juice (A strange drink as it came in a bowl filled with ice and jelly strips that resembles slugs and a dark liquid, but it was quite refreshing - needed both a straw and a spoon). Our friends arrived, and food was ordered.... 3 x Kao Soy Stewed Beef, 1x Kao Soy Poo-Nim ( which is a soft-shelled crab dish), Sai Oua (this is spicy sausage), Kai Satay (chicken on skewers with peanutbutter sauce). More drinks: another Beer, Soda Water and 2 x Passion Fruit Juices. The dishes were delicious.. really good fresh, tasty food. The prices seemed reasonable, we did eat a lot (a dish each and 2 shared dishes plus 1 or 2 drinks each) and the bill came to baht 1275.. that's about baht 320 each. The atmosphere was lively, there was a lot of staff around to help, and they were so polite and efficient. We will be returning to try other dishes on the menu.

Instagram: @ol_no_nichijoramen Khao Soi Gai - 85 Baht This popular Khao Soi spot is located around the Nimmanhaemin area in Chiang Mai. It's become well-known after being featured in the Michelin Bib Gourmand list. I visited around 4 PM on a Sunday, and since I opted for the terrace seating, there was no wait. Despite Chiang Mai's 38¬∞C heat, the fans on the terrace kept things pleasantly cool. I ordered the classic chicken Khao Soi, which arrived with thick boiled noodles topped with crispy fried noodles and cilantro. A separate plate with purple onions, pickled cabbage, and lime was also provided. The soup has a coconut-based Thai curry flavor. Initially mild, it develops a delightful spicy kick as you eat, making it quite addictive. The thick noodles soak up the soup beautifully, making each bite irresistible. The crispy noodles can be enjoyed either plain or dipped in the soup, offering a nice contrast in texture. The bone-in chicken topping was tender and fell apart easily with chopsticks, making it very easy to eat. I added all the purple onions, pickled cabbage, and lime to the soup during the meal, and each addition complemented the soup perfectly, keeping it flavorful and exciting until the very end. I ended up finishing every bit of the soup! We stumbled upon Kao Soy Nimman while taking a walk, drawn in by its charming decor. The restaurant offers plenty of seating both indoors and outdoors. Despite arriving at 4 PM, there were quite a few groups enjoying their meals. It was only later that we realized this place is Michelin-recommended‚Äîa pleasant surprise! We opted to sit outdoors, though indoor seating with air conditioning was available. Despite the hot weather, the standing fans kept the outdoor area comfortably cool. Initially, we planned to just have dessert, but the signature Khao Soi on the menu looked too appealing to resist, so we decided to share a bowl. We're glad we did! The noodles were cooked to perfection, and the Thai lime, onion, and salted vegetables added a unique twist that elevated the dish. For dessert, we ordered two options: the Passion and what I believe is called Chendo (though I‚Äôm not certain of the name). I preferred the Passion drink, which was refreshingly cool, though it wasn't as sour as I expected‚Äîit could have benefited from a stronger passion fruit flavor. The Chendo had a variety of ingredients, but it wasn't as fragrant or flavorful as similar desserts we‚Äôve had back home. Overall, I really enjoyed our visit and would love to return to try more of their dishes. The ambiance, food, and service made for a delightful experience.
My favorite khao soy whenever I visit Chiang Mai. Various menu and all tasty. Long queue during weekend. Better come weekday. Good atmosphere and good price.

Kao Soy Nimman, highlighted in the Michelin Guide, is a notable spot to experience khao soi in Chiang Mai. Michelin recognition attests to its quality and consistent appeal among locals and tourists. Khao soi itself is significant in Chiang Mai and Northern Thailand, known for its coconut-based curry broth, rich spices, and soft-crunchy noodle texture. A unique fusion of Thai and Burmese culinary influences, khao soi is cherished as a warm, hearty dish and has become an iconic part of Chiang Mai‚Äôs food culture, symbolizing local heritage and flavor. While it‚Äôs tourist-friendly and conveniently located, some visitors feel it‚Äôs slightly pricier than local spots nearby. It‚Äôs a recommended stop for travelers looking to try authentic Thai flavors.

One of the skewers is raw inside, notified staff. Staff was apologetic and offered not to charge the satay. Hopefully, i won't get food poisoning ü•≤üò≠ Butterfly pea flower lime juice: refreshing

We visited this restaurant twice, and both the food and the environment were great! However, by local standards, the pricing was indeed a bit on the higher side. We ordered the Khao Soi Stewed Beef, where the beef absorbed the delicious curry sauce, making it very flavorful, and the noodles were more elastic and chewy compared to others we've had elsewhere. We also tried the Rod Duan (fried bamboo worms), which had no strange taste but were instead filled with a bran-like aroma. We originally wanted to order grilled chicken, but customers at the next table who had ordered grilled chicken/pork/beef recommended we try the grilled beef, which proved to have an excellent flavor. Additionally, we tried the Thai Boiled Wild Mushrooms (Nam Prik Kha Hed Tob), which had a crisp texture and could be dipped in the provided Galangal Chili sauce, though I found that sauce to be a bit too spicy for me. For drinks, we tried Pennywort juice, Gardenia flower juice, and shelled coconut. Each had its unique flavor, but the portion sizes were quite small given the price. We avoided peak hours to escape the crowd and potential wait times, so during our visits, there were more servers than customers. They were all very enthusiastic and patient in introducing us to the dishes, and they responded quickly whenever we had questions or needed to add an order. If your travel budget isn‚Äôt too tight, we highly recommend giving this place a try.

This is my second visit to this restaurant, and the taste of their Khao Soi remains just as amazing as it was three years ago. I am thoroughly impressed with the consistency in the flavor. Khao Soi's taste is still delicious, and the best part is that it comes at an affordable price, making it truly a great value for money. The restaurant's Khao Soi brings back nostalgic memories of local cuisine. Their secret recipe has been kept intact, maintaining the authentic flavors of Chiang Mai. The aroma of the broth is rich, and the perfect level of spiciness adds to the irresistible allure of this dish. Apart from Khao Soi, their other dishes are also worth trying. Overall, this restaurant offers a good balance of quality and affordability. The service is friendly and efficient, further enhancing the dining experience. In conclusion, I highly recommend this restaurant once again. If you wish to savor authentic flavors of Chiang Mai, this place is an excellent choice. Their Khao Soi continues to be one of my favorite dishes, offering a delightful combination of taste and value. I look forward to revisiting this delightful eatery.

Yummy Kao Soy and definitely one of the best. Highly recommended for Kao Soy lovers. There were many options, Kao Soy with sai ua, with seafood, chicken and many others. My favourite is the combination of my two favourites in Chiang Mai,Kao Soy and sai ua.. sai is the yummiest pork sausage I have ever tasted. This place also serves great chicken satay with sweet peanut gravy. Really yummy. Also cendol, similar to Malaysian but without red beans, and other condiments. Pretty tasty nevertheless. Highly recommended to sai ua and Kao Soy lovers. Awesome hospitality from the staff and great ambience. Love this spot

This Michelin guide spot has incredible and there are typically large crowds‚Äî for good reason! Their Khao Soi is absolutely delicious, and we‚Äôre already planning to go back! Popular place among tourist since the banner at its shop front says it's featured in the Michellin Guide 2020. Price is on the highside by local standard. Very good quality Price Becarefull some dish can be very spicy

My favourite food in Chiangmai! We ordered 3 Khao Soi and the Mushroom Dip, my Thai friend previously brought me we tried their traditional dips too. Remember to dig in their northern Thai sausages when you are there because it‚Äôs a must eat to me too! Khao Soi taste like curry noodle with the flat egg noodle, served with whichever meat you pick and lots of ‚Äúwanton‚Äù skin which is my fav üòã it‚Äôs not too spicy for me (I‚Äôm a Singaporean that usually don‚Äôt eat spicy food) Loved their dessert as they are pretty generous with the fillings, it has a flower taste to it besides having the main coconut taste. Not worth the hype or the very long wait (can be 30 mins plus wait time. Someone actually left while we were waiting and said he had been waiting for too long). The food is good and we enjoyed it especially the grilled beef (though you can get way cheaper and just as tasty at the street food carts) but the Kao Soy was underwhelming. I had the Kao Soy Super Bowl and the prawns (aka shrimp) in it had a papery texture like when you freeze and defrost seafood. Didn‚Äôt taste fresh. The chicken drumstick in there was moist but was surprisingly bland and lacked the flavour I have come to expect from northern Thai food. The broth was nice and spicy and overall it was a tasty meal but just not worth the very long wait and the prices (we got 4 dishes and 3 drinks). The best Kao Soy we had was one we made ourselves at Mama Noi Thai Cookery School so definitely try that out if you‚Äôre a foodie. You‚Äôll get delicious food and learn how to make it on your own whilst having a fun experience. If you really want to try the food here then maybe order it to go so you can pick it up later without having to sit around waiting or see if you can order it to be delivered to your accommodation via Grab.

Very busy restaurant with good service and delicious Khao Soy options. Even though busy no one ever needed to wait for a table. The taste was good but maybe average for many other areas in the north for comparison.

Lack of value, the food quality doesn‚Äôt match its price. The most disappointing thing is the waiter only smiled when welcomed us to have dinner here. During our dinner, he was talking n laughing with other staff just besides us, but when I asked for a pair of chopsticks, the smile disappeared on the waiter‚Äôs face.

Date of Visit: August 22nd This is a famous restaurant in Chiang Mai, selected alongside Khao Soi Mae Sai in the Michelin Bib Gourmand. I visited during lunchtime, but there were plenty of seats, so I could order without waiting. The portion size felt larger than at Khao Soi Mae Sai, the price is a bit higher. If you don't like the strong flavor of curry, this place might be more suitable.

Yo, foodies! If you're in Chiang Mai and your tummy's rumbling for a taste of heaven, Kao Soi Nimman is your next stop. This no-frills gem in the center of town specializes in one thing, and they do it oh-so-right: Khao Soi! Tips for your visit: - Lunchtime gets busy, so plan accordingly. - Cash is king, but they might accept cards too. - Come hungry, portions are generous! - Prepare for a flavor explosion ‚Äì your taste buds will thank you! P.S. Don't forget to leave some room for their refreshing butterfly pea tea ‚Äì the perfect cool-down after your curry feast!

Popular with tourists from South Korea and mainland China. Be prepared to wait 20 - 30 min for a table during weekday lunchtime. The food was all too salty for me personally. The braised pork topping was nice though. Tender and flavourful. Noodle portions are very small for those with single topping. The one with assorted toppings had more noodles. I found the noodles rather soggy but that could be my personal preference (I like my noodles al dente). Soup was alright. Chicken skewers were tender but salty. Dessert with assorted toppings was tasty and refreshing. Outdoor seating can be quite warm. Staff can speak basic English (they could not understand my request not to give me a straw for the dessert)

Really nice restaurant from the food till the service, we are a couple of dishes including the famous Khao Soi, and it was delicious with Pork. We also ate another Spicy Chicken with bamboo shoots, not much to eat tho almost all the ingredients are spices or things for cooking. Anyhow I definitely recommend the place for people visiting the city for the first time and you want to sit in a vibrant area with a great atmosphere.

The khao soi here lives up to the hype! My friend took me here, and I was unaware of its reputation. The beef khao soi was my personal favorite, it's so tender and mixes perfectly with the curry. And if you live in Chiangmai or you‚Äôre passing through definitely worth coming here to try the local cuisine.

Checked out Kao Soy Nimman, a spot that's got a nod from Michelin, so you know it's got some serious creds. True to the hype, the place was packed, with a no-reservations policy meaning you grab a number and hang tight for your turn. Dropped by on a weekday, post-lunch rush around 2pm, and still clocked a 40-minute wait. Went straight for their namesake dish, the Kao Soy. Pretty tasty, though it leaned towards the saltier side - flavor lovers would be into it. The chicken BBQ was alright, nothing to write home about. Price-wise, it's a winner, and the vibe of the restaurant is pretty chill, albeit super busy. They could do with a few more hands on deck, as getting the bill took a bit of effort and a couple of reminders. Was the wait worth it? Depends on your mood and schedule. If you're looking to kill some time and escape the heat, it's not a bad option. But if you're not up for the wait, maybe swing by during off-peak hours.

I ordered Khao Soi beef , chicken skewers and the dessert The beef was a bit tough and not as tender as expected and the gravy is rather thick and Smokey . The chicken skewers is good , loving the nutty sauce and the juiciness and tenderness of the chicken .

I had to try the northern dish Khao Soi, while in Chiang Mai. We had walked past the restaurant, the day before and it was packed. We came back and were very pleased with the dish. My wife had the option with chicken leg, and I the fried pork. There is seating both inside and outside. The chili paste was also excellent.

For Khao Soi with fried pork. The soup is normal. I did not find the special from its taste. The crispy yellow noodles is hard, I put soup into it and waited for a while. The fried pork is very sticky, given just a very very few vegetables (so stinky! ) . Another side dish is fried dumplings, this one is good and nice smell of herbs. The outdoor area have a lot of mosquitoes, the staffs seem to know about this issue but ignorance. So overall, do not recommend.

We tried Khao Soi with seafood it was really delicious! PS: it's a famous restaurant, we had to queue to get a table but it was fast and the service was great!
Very delicious food and interesting menu!

Was here before 10am, hence no q when they started serve. Service and atmosphere is good. Ordered The curry noodles topping with fried crispy noodles & chicken leg / fried pork. Too much fried crispy noodles, not really able to soak the curry, don't feel really match the taste. The curry noodles somehow overated. Very oily and lack of aroma of curry. Maybe this is the taste of khao soi...XD

Recommended!!!! I like Kao Soy here. It‚Äôs just a little bit spicy so it‚Äôs easy to eat. So many toppings available for us to choose. The drinks and desserts menu are also interesting. I tried super bowl which I think it‚Äôs a lot for me. I like Khai Satay too. It‚Äôs impressive visiting there. I would recommend you all to try.

We were craving for Kao Soy and we found this on Google Maps, never noticed this is a Michelin Restaurant until we reached there then only we knew. I think it's because of peak hour, the staff are all busy to approach us, so we kind of wait for some time for the table and also ordering. We ordered two different types of Kao Soy, the taste is okay but doesn't taste any spicy, we are not sure what the taste is supposed to be because this is our first time having Kao Soy üòÑ Not to mention, the dessert can taste the ice from the icebox üòÇ Again, we are not sure if that is 'normal' tastes? Overall it is okay, will try the other Kao Soy restaurant in future.

This was a Michelin guide 2020 restaurant recommended to us from a Chiang Mai local. We waited a good 30 minutes but they churn people through the restaurant pretty quickly. The khao soi was absolutely delicious. I got the pork belly Khao soi and the pork belly melts in your mouth. The soup base had lots of herbs and spices with a little bit of curry based influenced. My favorite part was how the noodles were both crispy and soft. Soft for the parts in the soup and crispy for the pieces above it. I loved that combination of textures in this dish. We also got some delicious sides, calamari, chicken satay, and dumplings. All very good. So overall it was totally worth the wait and the prices are fair. Would 100% recommend going here.

This wasn't the best Khao Soi I've had in Chiang Mai; the broth seemed a bit bland. The prices here are quite high compared to other places but if you want to try a place on the Michelin guide you pay the price. They charge you for a bowl of ice about 20 baht. Very famous among tourists and can be crowded during lunch. We had to wait in a queue for about 40 mins. Besides the signature Khao Soi, we ordered several side dishes. The crispy pork skewers tasted quite good but not crispy, we had the mango sticky rice, the portion is huge but taste was just average. However, the dining environment is nice. This place is quite famous, but I think it's overrated.

Loved their khao soi dish! It was my first time but it was excellent choice to visit this restaurant. Very comfortable settings and friendly staff! Came here twice during my stay in Chiang Mai and never disappointed! No wonder why it is listed in Michelin 2020 & 2021!

This place is a little pricy for Kao Soy but the food is wonderful and a great place to take your guests for experiencing local Kao Soy flavors and atmosphere. I wish they had an option of the bigger portion for all Kao Soys but only for house special. Floor staff were well trained and always were checking each table.

I would say the stewed beef Kao Soy was delicious as was the pork but the beef had a much better flavor. The pork kao soy could have used another scoop of broth. Kao Soy Nimman is one of the uniqueness place serving Khao Soi with plenty of meat to add on for topping. Not only the Khao Soi availble here, they also served the Northern Thai‚Äôs dishes and Thai sweet. The bow of Khao Soi is good with the light soup but intense in aroma of curry paste, the soup is quite sweet not to spicy even adding some chili to it. This is a good place to enjoy the Northern Thai food, if you getting bored of Khao Soi.

I went there bcs I was in the area and they got michelin so I thought "Why don't just try it?". No waiting line at around 2.30 PM. The service is quite nice and fast. Kao Soy Nimman is a popular restaurant located in the trendy Nimman area of Chiang Mai. The restaurant specializes in Kao Soy, a traditional northern Thai dish that consists of a rich and flavorful curry broth served with tender chicken or beef and crispy noodles. The restaurant's cozy ambiance and friendly service make it a great spot for a casual meal with friends or family. In addition to Kao Soy, the menu also features a variety of other northern Thai dishes, as well as some international options. Overall, Kao Soy Nimman is a great place to enjoy some delicious northern Thai cuisine in a relaxed setting.

Kao Soy Nimman, located in Chiang Mai‚Äôs trendy Nimman area, is renowned for its rich and flavorful Khao Soi, a Northern Thai coconut curry noodle soup. The restaurant offers a variety of protein options, including chicken, beef, pork, seafood, and Chiang Mai sausage, allowing diners to customize their bowls. The broth is praised for its depth and balance, combining creamy coconut milk with aromatic spices, and the noodles are perfectly cooked, complemented by crispy fried noodles on top. In addition to Khao Soi, the menu features other Northern Thai specialties and refreshing herbal drinks like gardenia and pennywort.

Forgettable and average khao soi. It has a very nice decor, comfortable and clean environment. There's indoor air conditioned seating and outdoor seating. Even seating outdoors, there's no pesky mosquitoes. There are many wait staff and they are attentive and helpful. There's a toilet and free wifi. However when it comes to the food, it's mediocre and i have had better khao soi in the basement of a fresh market and much cheaper too. The khao soi here is served in a porcelain bowl with the pickle, onion and lime wedge in a separate metal dish. One taste of the noodle, the soup was not hot(merely warm), noodle was too soft and the curry tasted a tad too sweet(not sour enough even with the lime). I ordered the thai omelette khao soi, the omelette itself was good and the fried egg noodles on top of the bowl were perfectly crispy and crunchy so props for those. Overall forgettable khao soi and it was more expensive than average (starts at 69 thb. I have had better khao soi at 40 thb). I went past the kitchen and noticed a big vat of curry boiling away on the stove so it doesn't make sense that it's merely warm. I try to avoid single use plastics and always have with me my own cutlery. Such an upscale place and they use single use plastics and chopsticks. Disappointing. (Returning the plastics will only be thrown in the bin so even worse)

This review might seem spiteful, but I truly had a very poor experience here that is likely to be reflective of the general quality of the restaurant. Kao Soy Nimman is a Michelin bib gourmand place which has definitely earned it much fame among tourists. We had to line up for about 30 minutes before being given a table, which isn‚Äôt a problem in itself. However, ONCE we got inside and placed our orders (one bowl of khao soi and one omelette), it took 40 minutes before the khao soi arrived. We made several requests to the staff about where our food was, but no one ever seemed to be able to definitively help. The khao soi took 40 minutes to arrive, but we waited about 70 minutes for the omelette and it never came. We ultimately decided we had spent too long in the restaurant, asked the waitress if we could cancel our omelette request (to which she kindly said yes), paid up and left. As for the khao soi, it was extremely bland and watered down, and the meat was tough and chewy. I have since eaten at Khao Soi Maesai and Khao Soi Lung Prakit Kad Kom (both Michelin bib gourmand places too), and their khao soi was incomparably better and the quality of the meat was far superior too. Not to mention, the prices at this restaurant are 3x those at the other two, but for what reason? This isn‚Äôt an agenda-driven review by any means, but simply an honest reflection of what I experienced. I hope it is helpful, especially to those of you who are considering visiting on a tight time schedule - you will not miss anything important by skipping this place.

My husband loves khao soi, so we were on the hunt for the best khao soi in town, and saw the great reviews on this place! Although not the best khao soi, it was pretty delicious! When we got there around lunch time, there was a huge line up! We contemplated waiting or not, but ultimately decided to since we were there anyways and we really wanted to try this place out. We got our number from the hostess and she told us there were 20 numbers ahead of us so we were prepared to wait for at least an hour. There is a bubble tea place right beside it so we ordered a bubble tea while we waited. To our surprise, the wait only took about 25 minutes! We got seated in the air-conditioned space at the back, which was good because it was such a hot day out! I ordered the chicken khao soi, my husband ordered the beef khao soi, and we also got the crispy wontons and steamed vegetables to share. The food came within 10 minutes, which was very reasonable. The khao soi tasted quite good, just the right amount of richness, and not too spicy. Since this place is so popular among tourists, we felt that perhaps the dish was not truly authentic, compared to some other khao soi we have tried. Delicious food nonetheless! The food was definitely tourist pricing since it was pricier than most other local restaurants, but we expected that going in so no surprises there. I would definitely return to this place if I find myself in Chiang Mai again, but I‚Äôd probably try to go a bit earlier to avoid the lunch time rush.

Oh, and when I wanted to order a beer they told me beer was sold out (at 7pm), which I found was strange‚Ä¶ Both dishes cost about 120 baht each.

This seems to be a social Media made hot Spot! Food is Dissapointing! I had a much better Koa Soy in a local shop the other day for half the Price. I had it with beef5, which was mainly fat. Nothing special at all but random Koi Soy dish. Service is quick, because there are many people.

I was disappointed with my experience. There was a queue, mostly tourists like myself. Restaurant is clean and tidy, presentable, with prices higher than elsewhere (75 baht instead of 55-60 baht) catered towards the tourist crowd. Portion size was good for sampling at best (2 mouthfuls and done). Khao soi here was not crazy good, unlike what the Michelin guide sticker on the doorfront would suggest. Would recommend Mae Sai instead if in the area for Khao Soi. You got to queue at either places anyway.
Food is good but a bit pricy but it's clean especially wash room

Unforgettable experience! The service, the smiling faces in the kitchen! You‚Äôll wait in line probably for 5-10 mins, but be patient cuz good things come to those who wait! xxx

Very delicious. I've ordered ~ 10 times now - always Khao Soi with Chicken + 1 Chicken thigh. Price is around ‡∏ø140 including delivery in the area. Sometimes Grab offers promotions. The only downside to this culinary gem is that Thai food at home will never be good enough again. Kao Soy (Khao Soi) is a Northern Thai specialty that is everything you love about noodle soups but with a little extra Thai zing.
